A numerical implementation and analysis of Ridge, Lasso and OLS on the Franke function and on terrain data.¶

Karl Jacobsen

Program instruction¶

In order to run this as a notebook, the file "classesRegression.py" must be stored in the same directory as this notebook.

Abstract¶

Ridge and OLS estimators are implemented from scratch and applied to data made from the Franke function and terrain data from Norway. In addition the Lasso model from Sci-Kit learn was used. Both the Ridge and the OLS-estimators applies the SVD decomposition, reducing the probability of matrix inversion issues. The OLS-model always has the lowest training MSE. The training MSE always decreases with the degrees of freedom, while this is not the case for the testing MSE. Bias-variance decomposition of the MSEs from K-fold cross validation shows that the variance in the MSE of MSEs from the OLS-model in the Franke function case makes the test MSE increase with degrees of freedom. For the terrain data, however, the test MSE does not go down for the highest degree of freedom, suggesting absence of overfitting. Bootstrapping and doing a bias-variance decomposition over the full domain for the Franke-function generated data, suggests that there is not overfitting for the OLS model for the degrees applied throughout this report. The results from the bootstrapping method suggests that overfitting of the Franke-function generated data does not take place before around 15 degrees of freedom. The R2 score seems to always follow the MSE score. The testing MSE is lower for the Ridge and Lasso than for the OLS-model. For Ridge and Lasso the variance does not increase as much with degrees of freedom as for the OLS-model, indicating that Ridge and Lasso are less prone to overfitting. The parameter uncertainties, measured as estimated parameter standard deviation to estimated parameter value, are lower for Ridge than for OLS. The residuals in the Franke case never seems to be Gaussian, making the equation for the parameter variances invalid. For the terrain data the residuals looks more Gaussian. The parameter uncertainties and the MSEs, both training and testing, increase considerably when Gaussian noise is added to the Franke function. The residuals still does not seem Gaussian. The models for the terrain data were tested on a test set where all test points lay outside the training region. The results on the test set was much weaker than the test MSEs from the cross validations.

Introduction¶

OLS is the most used regression model. There are a lot of statistical packages that offeres OLS, and complex analysis can be done by only a few clicks. Because of its wide use, it is important to understand the OLS-model. In order to understand the model, it is useful to build ones own OLS-model up from scratch. This will be done in this report, where OLS togehter with the Ridge model will be programmed.

One of the mistakes that is easy making in statistical analysis is overfitting. The fit becomes better and better on the data we are fitting the model to. On the other hand, good training data fit does not necessaraly imply that the model generalizes well outside the training data. The model may perform much worse outside the training data. This is called overfitting. Since most models are made to be used outside the training domain, it is very important to have knowledge about overfitting.

Overfitting will be studied by the use of the resampling techniques K-fold cross validation and bootstrapping. These are central techniques in applied data analysis. Hence understanding of how the techniques work is of central importance. We will write our own K-fold cross validation and bootstrapping methods.

Overfitting is related to the variance component of the MSE of a model. It will be shown that the MSE can be decomposed into a variance component and a bias component. Furthermore we implement the bias-variance decomposition into our class, and study it for all models and scenarios.

Lasso and Ridge are models that are more resistent to overfitting compared to the OLS model, and often used in practice. The Ridge model will be implemented from scratch here.

The Ridge and Lasso models both depend on a user-given punishment parameter. The punishment parameter can affect the model performance greatly. We will study the effect on this parameter on the model performance, and find optimal values of these punishment parameters.

Real data is often noisy. Hence it is important to know what the effects of noise on the model are. We study the effect of noise by comparing the estimation results on the Franke data with and witout noise. MSEs and also estimated parameter variances are analysed in the study of the effects of noise.

Almost all of the above tasks are performed on both the Franke generated data and the terrain data. This allows us to investigate the difference between statistical analysis on real world data and synthetic data. This is important having knowledge about, since most statistical analysis is done on real data.

We will apply the models trained on the terrain on a neigbor terrain that has not taken part in the training. This will show how good the test MSEs from the resampling technique are as indicators for real testing MSE.

In order to ensure the quality of own made methods, it is important to test these methods. We test the own made OLS, Ridge and K-fold cross validation methods against the corresponding methods from Sci-Kit learn.

Next we will briefly present the main theory. The results section of the report is divided in two. The first part deals with the Franke function scenario, while the second part deals with the Terrain scenario. A section about testing follows the results section, and finally there are some conclusions and references.

Theory¶

All the regression estimators are solutions to minimization problems where a cost function is minimized. The difference between the estimators comes from differences in the cost functions.

Since OLS can be interpreted as a special case of Ridge regression, we treat Ridge and OLS together. The Ridge optimization problem is

\begin{align} arg \min_{\beta} \Big( \sum_{i=1}^N (y_i - \tilde{y}_i)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^P \beta_j^2\Big), \end{align}

where

\begin{align} \tilde{y_i}= \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^P x_{ij} \beta_j \end{align}

For OLS we have $\lambda = 0$.

Rewriting the above problem to matrix-vector form an taking derivatives gives

\begin{align} \hat{\beta}^{Ridge} = (\hat{X}^T \hat{X} + \lambda \hat{I}) \hat{X}^T \hat{y} \end{align}

For Lasso the following optimization problem is solved for $\beta$:

\begin{align} arg \min_{\beta} \Big( \sum_{i=1}^N (y_i - \tilde{y}_i)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^P |\beta_j|\Big). \end{align}

Estimators for the parameter variances for Ridge can be derived assuming that the entries of $y$ are uncorrelated and all have the same variance equal to the assumed normall distributed error term. From p. 10 in Wieringen (2018) we get

\begin{align} Var(\hat{\beta})^{Ridge} = \hat{W} \sigma^2 (\hat{X}^T \hat{X})^{-1} \hat{W}^T, \end{align}

where

\begin{align} \hat{W} = (\hat{X}^T \hat{X} + \lambda \hat{I}) \hat{X}^T \hat{X} \end{align}

We see that for OLS, where $\lambda = 0$, we get $\hat{W} = \hat{I}$.

We will make use of the SVD-decomposition when estimating the Ridge and OLS-models. Using the SVD, our numerical computations are less sensitive to almost singular matrices, which typically arises when overfitting. By plugging the SVD decomposition $\hat{X} = \hat{U} \hat{D} \hat{V}^T$ into the coefficient formula for the Ridge estimator Wieringen (2018) p.8 gets

\begin{align} \hat{\beta}^{ridge} = \hat{V}(\hat{D}^2 + \lambda \hat{I})^{-1} \hat{D} \hat{U}^T \hat{y} \end{align}

OLS. Error analysis¶

In the study of modell performance, it is crusial to distinguiss between performance measured on a test set and on the training data itself. By comparing the performance of different polynomial degrees by MSE and R2 from traning data, one will probaly not find the best model. The error measures for the training data typically always decreases with the complexity of the model, leading to the false conclusion that the more complex the model, the better. The problem with a highly complex model, is that the predictions from this model will be highly variable with the input. A model very senesitive to the input data, does not generalize well, meaning that the model does not work well for other data than the data it was created with. This problem is called overfitting.

Overfitting can be measured by measruing the prediction error from a given model on data that was not used in estimating the model. We split the data in training and test sets. Techniques for splitting the data in test and training sets are called resampling techniques.

We will apply the K-fold resampling technique. With the F-fold method, the data is split in K number of folds. One of the folds are chosen as the testing set, while the remaining folds are used for traning the model. This is repeated K number of times, each time with a different fold as the test set. We get K models, and we compute the error measures for all of them. Finally we averge the error measures over the models, getting scalars for the error measures for the given polynoial degree.

The following code calls uppon the own made class and perform K-fold cross validation when applying OLS. Both the OLS-model and the Ridge model has been tested against Sci-Kit learn, and the results are identical. The test results are found in the section "Testing: Sci-kit learn comparisons". The implemented K-fold method was tested against Sci-Kit learn's K-fold method. The results were alsmost identical. See the section "Testing: Sci-kit learn comparisons" for the test results.

We produce figures for $MSE_{training}$, $MSE_{testing},\; R2_{training}$ and $R2_{testing}$ as functions of the polynomial degree.

def FrankeFunction(x,y):
    term1 = 0.75*np.exp(-(0.25*(9*x-2)**2) - 0.25*((9*y-2)**2))
    term2 = 0.75*np.exp(-((9*x+1)**2)/49.0 - 0.1*(9*y+1))
    term3 = 0.5*np.exp(-(9*x-7)**2/4.0 - 0.25*((9*y-3)**2))
    term4 = -0.2*np.exp(-(9*x-4)**2 - (9*y-7)**2)
    return term1 + term2 + term3 + term4

Figure 2b: R2 score. OLS. Franke scenario.

The figure to the left above shows that for the training set the MSE always decreases with the degrees of freedom. We also see that the K-fold method gives higher MSE compared to the training set. Contrary to the training MSE, the K-fold MSE reaches a point where more complexity with regards to polynomial degree does not make the fit better. The best polynomial degree seems to be 4, since the MSE of the K-fold method is higher for the other values.

Another way to study the fit, is by computation of the so-called R2-score. An R2-score equalt to one is a perfect fit, and the R2 is normally between zero and one. The figure to the right above shows the same story as the figure to the left, suggesting best fit is for degree 4.

Furthermore, we see that the quality of the fit for the training set becomes extremely good, since the R2-score approaches one when the degrres of freedom increse.

The reason for the increase in MSE with complexity has to do with increased variance due with model complexity. When the model is complex, a small change in the data will affect the estimation results to a high degree. Hence the MSE will vary a lot between the different folds in the K-fold validations when the model is complex.

The following code produces a figure, where we have decomposed the MSE of all MSE's at given degrees of freedom into contributions from the squared bias and the variance, showing the contributing factors behind the change in MSE. Before turning to the code, we put up the equations for this bias-variance decomposition.

We derive the equations from the equation for the variance of a variable $x$:
\begin{align} Var(x) &= \frac{1}{N} \sum_i (x_i - \bar{x})^2 \\ &= \frac{1}{N} \sum_i (x_i^2 - 2\bar{x} x_i + \bar{x}^2) \\ &= \frac{1}{N} \sum_i (x_i^2) - 2\bar{x}^2 + \bar{x}^2) \\ &= \frac{1}{N} \sum_i (x_i^2) - \bar{x}^2 \\ \frac{1}{N} \sum_i (x_i^2) &= Var(x) + \bar{x}^2 \end{align}

The expression says that the mean square of a variable equals the sum of the variance and the squared mean mean of that variable. If we now put the MSE's from the cross validation as $x_i$ in the equation, we have a decomposition of the mean square of the MSEs from the K-folds validation into the variance of the MSEs and the mean of the MSEs. The mean of the MSEs can be interpreted as a bias. If the mean of the MSEs equals zero, the model on average fits the data perfectly, i.e. the model is unbiased. I will use the term the decomposition of MSE of MSEs for the bias-variance decomposition performed from this exrepssion.

Now lets see how this works out on the OLS data.

The variance increases with the degrees of freedom, while the bias decreases with the degrees of freedom.

The figure above shows that the bias contribution to the K-folds MSE decreeses, while the variance constribution increases, with the degrees of freedom. This observation, reduced bias and increased variance with complexity, is classical for overfitting.

We have found tha the OLS model due to increased variance suffers from overfitting for the largest polynomial degree. Now we will have a look at two models that are less sensitive to overfitting.

A better bias-variance decomposition: Bootstrap¶

The bias-variance decomposition above is very rough, as it only works on the aggregate MSEs for the different test-folds. With this method each point is in the test set only once. Hence we do not get any information on how the prediction of a given point varies with the model. We are now going to use the formulae for the bias-variance decomposition derived above, but we'll use several observations per point in space. We can make multiple predictions on each position by applying the bootstrap method.

With bootstrapping random positions are drawn with replacement, and the total number of positions equals the size of the full data. Hence some positions will appear more than once for a bootstrap iteration. The positions that is not drawn are used as test set. This drawing is repeated multiple times, we say for multiple bootstraps.

By doing many bootstraps we get multiple predictions on each position in the domain. Hence we can study how the predictions on given positions varies with the model.

In the formulae above for bias-variance decomposition, $x_i$, which earlier was $MSE_i$ with $i$ being MSE from one K-fold iteration, is replaced by the residuals at a given point, $\delta_i$, where $i$ now represents different predictions at this given point. Note that now we get $MSE$ exactly, and not MSE of MSEs as with the K-fold method. Furthermore, the formula now applies to one single position in the domain.

The decomposition in the previous paragraph is computed for every position in the domain. Then averages over the domain are taken to give average bias, variance and MSE.

Note that this method differs from all methods discussed on Piazza. 1) It differs from the example made by Kristine, where the bias-variance decomposition is not over different models, but a decomposition of the MSE for a given model. 2) The method here differs from the method by Bendik on Piazza. Bendik applies the same test set each time, while I apply different test sets for every bootstrap, as described in Hastie et al. (2009). 3) Also, my method differs from Bendik's method and Hastie et al. (2009), as my formula is not based on the bias-variance decomposition of the true function. I only decompose the difference from the observations. Hence my noise-term spreads out into my bias and variance term.

Before applying the method, I will brefly list the algorithm in pseeudo code:

In [ ]:
for bootstrap:
    Draw sample of training observations
    The positions not drawn as training, performs as test set
    
    for all testObservations:
        error[testObservation].append(zTrue[testObservation] - zPredict[testObservation]
        
For all positions in domain:
    mse[position] = mean{ (error[position])**2 }
    var[position] = variance(error[position])
    bias2[position] = {mean(error[position])}**2

mseMean = mean(mse)
varMean = mean(var)
bias2Mean = mean(bias2)

Now lets use the above method to study the bias-variance decomposition for the OLS-model for polynomials up to degree 25.

Ridge and Lasso regression¶

Ridge and Lasso regression differs from OLS by including a punishment term in the cost-function. When model complexity is becoming large in the OLS-problem, giving overfitting, the design matrix becomes singular. By adding the penalty term the design matrix becomes invertible and Ridge and Lasso regression gives solutions.

For Ridge regression the penalty term equals the squared absolute value of coefficients times a chosen parameter, while for Lasso the penalty term equals the absolute value of coefficients times a chosen parameter. In contrast to Ridge regression, Lasso can give parameter values equal to zero, which is practical when determining relevant predictors.

The optimal value of the punishment parameters is unknowns, and varies from problem to problem. Next we will try identify the optimal value of the models' punishment parameters. The optimum will be tried found for degree five. We note that the optimum will depend on the degrees of freedom as well, so optimally we would have done this punismhemt parameter analysis for all degrees of freedom. However, the use of the Lasso and Ridge methods are often on the highest degrees, since these methods handles higher degrees well by adjusting the parameters.

From the figure to the left above we see that the training error is always lowest for the OLS-model. It was expected that the training error was lowest for the OLS model, because OSL minimizes the training error, while the other model minimizes different cost-functions than the training error.

In the middle figure above, we see that the rankings of model performance is turned around when one measures the model performance on test sets. 10-fold cross validation has been used. Now the OLS estimator performs worst for the higest degree of freedom. We see that in contrast to OLS, the Ridge and the Lasso model do not get the sudden explosion in test MSE when the degree become five. The punishment terms makes the Ridge and the Lasso estimators avoid the problem with nearly singular matrices when the model complexity gets high.

The figure to the right, which shows the variance share of total MSE, illustrats the effect of the punishment terms in the Ridge and the Lasso estimators. The punishment term reduces the test MSE by reducing the variance. When the punishment term is large, there is a large punishment for large parameter values. Hence the parameter values are pressed down a lot when the punishment term is large. With lower parameter values, the models react less when applied to new test sets. Hence the variance contribution to MSE is reduced with the introduction of penalty terms.

The middle figure above suggests that the complexity can increase even more when applying the Ridge or the Lasse estimators. Without looking at the coefficient values, it can be misleading only looking at the degrees of freedom number to determine the optimal degrees of freedom. With Ridge and Lasso, several parameters can be close to zero, so that the effective degrees of freedom is less than what was sent into the model. This is a strength with the Ridge and Lasso estimator's. We can use high degrees of freedom, and the models themselves decides which of the parameters it will actually use, so we migth avoid doing this degrees of freedom analysis that we have done til now.

Parameter uncertainties¶

Another way to compare the models, is by comparison of their parameter uncertainties. If the random errors are normally distributed, there is a formula for estimation of the variance of the parameters. Applying this formula we will compare the standard deviation of the three first parameters in polynomial fits from degree one to degree five. The three first parameters were chosen, since these parameters appear inn all the polynomial fits. Furthermore, we will report the standard deviation divided by the absolute value of the corresponding parameter estimate. Comparing the ratios of standard deviation to parameter values allows us to say something more about the condidence intercal of the parameter.

The following code produces the uncertainty values for the five first parameters for all degrees up to five.

In [8]:
models = 'ols', 'ridge'
ridgeLambda = startLambdaRidge*adjustmentFactorRidge
lambdaValues = 0, ridgeLambda
for model, lambdaValue in zip(models, lambdaValues):
    tst1.varBetaFigures(model=model, ridgeLambda=lambdaValue)

Figure 6: Parameter uncertainty. OLS. Franke scnario.

Figure 7: Parameter uncertainty. Ridge. Franke scnario.
For the highest degree, for which the punishment parameters i tuned for, the Ridge regression gives lower paramameter uncertainties.

We see that the findings from the MSE analysis is supported by the parameter uncertainties. The parameter uncertainties are reduced in the Ridge model compared to the OLS model, which again gives lower variance in the bias-variance decomposition.

The effects of noise on MSE¶

Til now we have used the pure Franke-function as input to our data without any extra noise. If the Franke-function had been in the Span of our basis functions, we would have gotten a perfect fit with zero error. However, our basis functions do not span the Franke-function. Hence we do not get a perfect fit. There will always be an error.

In order to see what the effect of noise is on the estimators, we now add more noise, of the NIID type, to the data. In the titles the term "noise" equals the factor $\eta$ in $y = f(x) + \eta \varepsilon,\;\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)$. The following code produces figures for MSE and the bias-variance decomposition.

Parameter uncertainty and the effects of noise¶

Now we'll take a look at how the variance of the estimated parameters depends on the polynomial degree.

We will study the parameter variances for the OLS-estimation on the full set. The next figure shows the standard deviation to parameter value for the three first parameters, for noise parameters $\eta = 0$ and $\eta = 0.5$ in $y = f(x) + \eta \varepsilon,\;\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0,1)$.

In [10]:
noises = [0.0, .5]
tst1.varBetaFigures(noises=noises)

Figure 10: Standard deviation/Estimation value coefficients. OLS. No noise. Franke scenario.

Figure 11: Standard deviation/Estimation value coefficients. OLS. Noise. Franke scenario.
The effect of degrees of freedom is the same as for the case without noise. The standard deviations relative to the parameter values are much higher in the noise case than in the case without noise.

First we note from the figures that the relation between parameter uncertainty and model complexity relates to the previous finding that uncertainty increases with model complexity. From the figure above we see that the uncertainty in the paremeter estimates increases with the model complexity. In other words, the confidence intervals widens with the polynomial degree. For normally distributed variables, a 95 per cent confidence interval is approximately $[\hat{\beta} - 2 Sd(\hat{\beta}), \hat{\beta} + 2 Sd(\hat{\beta})]$. The values in the figures above suggest that in the presence of extra noise, the limits of some of the confidence interval's are larger than the parameters themselves. Even the sign of the parameters are uncertain. Hence the parameter estimates are very uncertain.

We also see that larger variance in the stochastic error term has a huge impact on the parameter variances. The values in the second figure above is much larger compared to the corresponding values in the first figure.

The formula applied for the parameter variances describe noise due to stochastic errors. In our case, where the true model is not spanned by our basis functions, the MSE includes this error from use of wrong basis functions. An alternative interpretation is that the extra error, the error in addition to the Gaussian noise, is due to measurement errors. If the total error, the sum of the Gaussian error and the extra error, is normally distributed, the equation used for the parameter variances applied in the figures above should still hold.

In order to study whether the normality assumtion about the errors for the parameter variance formula holds, we now study the distribution of the residuals in our fit with the OLS-model.

In [11]:
noises=[0, 0.5] 
nBins=25
tst1.createResidualHistograms(noises=noises, nBins=nBins)

Figure 12: Residuals. OLS. No noise. Franke scenario.

Figure 13: Residuals. OLS. Noise. Franke scenario.
With noise the distribution becomes much wider.

From the first figure above we see that the original residual distribution does not seem to be very Gaussian. Hence the interpretation of the extra error, the error when there is no Gaussian noise added, as being random normally distributed disturbances in the data does not to be very good.

The second plot in above shows that adding Gaussian noise does not make the residuals look Gaussian eighter. The residuals get more spread out in the presence of Gaussian noise. The stregnth of the Gaussion noise is not large enough compared to the "extra error" to make the residuals Gaussian.

We condlude that we do not have Gaussian error terms. However, Hastie et al. (2009) p. 49 states that the condidence intervals of the parameters are not much changed when the assumption of Gaussian noise is relaxed. Hence we still have faith in the calculated parameter variances above.

Terrain data¶

In [12]:
def FrankeFunction(x,y):
    term1 = 0.75*np.exp(-(0.25*(9*x-2)**2) - 0.25*((9*y-2)**2))
    term2 = 0.75*np.exp(-((9*x+1)**2)/49.0 - 0.1*(9*y+1))
    term3 = 0.5*np.exp(-(9*x-7)**2/4.0 - 0.25*((9*y-3)**2))
    term4 = -0.2*np.exp(-(9*x-4)**2 - (9*y-7)**2)
    return term1 + term2 + term3 + term4

def surface_plot(surface,title):
    M,N = surface.shape

    ax_rows = np.arange(M)
    ax_cols = np.arange(N)

    [X,Y] = np.meshgrid(ax_cols, ax_rows)

    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.gca(projection='3d')
    ax.plot_surface(X,Y,surface,cmap=cm.viridis,linewidth=0)
    plt.title(title)

Evaluation against the test set¶

The finding here is that it is a much harder task evaluating a model totally outside the training data!

Testing: Sci-kit learn comparisons¶

This section includes comparison of our own methods with corresponding Sci-Kit learn methods.

Test of OLS and Ridge¶

The following code, which also contains its results, shows that our class produces the same parameter estimates, the same predictions and the same errors as Ridge for both the OLS-estimator and the Ridge-estimator.

In [22]:
# Scitkit learn. Testing whether our code gives the same mse and R2 on the training set as scl.
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

x = np.arange(0, 1, .05)#0.05)
y = np.arange(0, 1, .05)#0.05)

xPlot, yPlot = np.meshgrid(x,y)

def FrankeFunction(x,y):
    term1 = 0.75*np.exp(-(0.25*(9*x-2)**2) - 0.25*((9*y-2)**2))
    term2 = 0.75*np.exp(-((9*x+1)**2)/49.0 - 0.1*(9*y+1))
    term3 = 0.5*np.exp(-(9*x-7)**2/4.0 - 0.25*((9*y-3)**2))
    term4 = -0.2*np.exp(-(9*x-4)**2 - (9*y-7)**2)
    return term1 + term2 + term3 + term4

zPlot = FrankeFunction(xPlot, yPlot)

x = np.reshape(xPlot, -1, 1)
y = np.reshape(yPlot, -1, 1)
z = np.reshape(zPlot, -1, 1)


XHat = np.c_[x, y]
degree = 5
poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree)
XHat = poly.fit_transform(XHat)

regressionTypes = 'LS', 'Ridge'
for regressionType in regressionTypes:
    print('\n ##################Regression type: %s' %regressionType, '################## \n')
    if regressionType == 'LS':
        lambdaValue = None
        linreg = LinearRegression()
        linreg.fit(XHat, z)
        predictScitKit = linreg.predict(XHat)

    else:
        lambdaValue = 2
        linreg=linear_model.Ridge(alpha=lambdaValue, fit_intercept = False) #False
        #XHatSCL = np.c_[np.ones_like(x), x, y]
        #XHatSCL = np.c_[x, y]
        #XHatSCL = XHat
        #linreg.fit(XHatSCL, z)
        #predictScitKit = linreg.predict(XHatSCL)
    print('################### Sci-kit learn############################')
    
    linreg.fit(XHat, z)
    predictScitKit = linreg.predict(XHat)


    print('Intercept: ', linreg.intercept_)
    print('Coefficients: ', linreg.coef_)
    print("Mean squared error: %.4f" % mean_squared_error(z, predictScitKit))
    print('R2 score: %.4f' % r2_score(z, predictScitKit))

    print('\n################### My class############################')

    ls = LeastSquares(xPlot, yPlot, zPlot, degree,trueFunction=FrankeFunction, lambdaValue=lambdaValue)
    ls.createDesignMatrix()
    ls.estimate()

    ls.predict()
    ls.calculateErrorScores()

K-fold cross validation.¶

Here we compare the average test MSE copmuted by our own model and Sci-Kit learn's K-fold method. The results are almost identical.

In [23]:
# Sci-kit learn Cross validation

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

fontSize = 15

np.random.seed(1)
observationNumber = 20
x = np.random.rand(observationNumber, 1)
x = np.sort(x, 0)
y = np.random.rand(observationNumber, 1)
y = np.sort(y, 0)

#x = np.linspace(0,1,5)
#y = np.linspace(0,1,5)
xPlot, yPlot = np.meshgrid(x,y)
zPlot = FrankeFunction(xPlot, yPlot)
x = np.reshape(xPlot, -1, 1)
y = np.reshape(yPlot, -1, 1)
z = np.reshape(zPlot, -1, 1)


def display_scores(scores):
    #print("Scores:", scores)
    #print("Mean:", scores.mean())
    #print("Standard deviation:", scores.std())
    return  scores.mean(), scores.std()

mses = []
mseKF = []
error = []
maxDegrees = 6
numberOfFolds = 10
linreg = LinearRegression()

for degree in range(1, maxDegrees+1):
    poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree)
    XHat = np.c_[x, y]
    XHat = poly.fit_transform(XHat)
    lin_scores = cross_val_score(linreg, XHat, z,
                             scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=numberOfFolds)
    lin_rmse_scores = -lin_scores
    mse, std = display_scores(lin_rmse_scores)
    mses.append(mse)
    
    lsKF = LeastSquares(xPlot, yPlot, zPlot, degree,trueFunction=FrankeFunction)
    lsKF.kFold(numberOfFolds=numberOfFolds)
    mseKF.append(np.mean(lsKF.mseSciKit))
    error.append(lsKF.totalError)

#print('\n Manually calculated MSE/ MSE sci-kit-function  \n', np.array(error)/np.array(mseKF))
    
degrees = np.arange(1, maxDegrees+1)
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
legends = ['Sci-Kit', 'Own method']#
methods = mses, mseKF#, error
for degree, method, label in zip(range(1, maxDegrees+1), methods, legends):
    ax.plot(degrees, method, label=label)
#fig.legend(legends)


ax.set_title('MSE', fontsize = fontSize*1.5)
ax.set_xlabel('Degrees of freedom', fontsize = fontSize*1.25)
ax.set_xticks(degrees)
box = ax.get_position()
ax.set_position([box.x0, box.y0, box.width * 1.0, box.height*.8])
ax.legend(legends, loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(-0.2, -0.55), \
           fontsize = fontSize, ncol=2)
ax.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=fontSize*1.25)

Conclusions¶

The Ridge and Lasso models does not have as low training MSE as the OLS-model. This was expected, since the OLS-model minimizes the training MSE.

Both the Franke data and the terrain data show that the training MSE is a bad approximation of the testing MSE, espaicially as the the number of degrees of freedom increases. The training MSE always decreases with the degrees of freedom, while this is not the case for the testing MSE.

The variance in the MSE of MSEs makes the test MSE of the OLS model particulary increase for the highest degrees of freedom in the Franke case, suggesting that we are overfitting. For the terrain data, however, there is no sign of overfitting. The test MSE does not go down for the highest degree of freedom for the terrain data.

Bootstrapping and doing a bias-variance decomposition over the full domain, suggests that there is not overfitting for the OLS model for the degrees applied throughout this report. The results from the bootstrapping method suggests that overfitting of the Franke-function generated data does not take place before around 15 degrees of freedom.

The R2 score seems to always follow the MSE score.

The testing MSE is lower for the Ridge and Lasso than for the OLS-model. For the test MSE, the Ridge and the Lasso model generally do better than the OLS-model. For Ridge and Lasso the variance does not increase as much with degrees of freedom as for the OLS-model, indicating that Ridge and Lasso are less prone to overfitting.

The above results for the models and overfitting is mirrored in the results for the parameter uncertainties. The parameter uncertainties are lower for Ridge than for OLS. The residuals in the Franke case never seems to be Gaussian, making the equation for the parameter variances invalid. For the terrain data the residuals looks more Gaussian.

The addition of noise to the Franke function has huge effects on the model results. The parameter uncertainties and the MSEs, both training and testing, increase considerably. The residuals still does not seem Gaussian.

Non of the models seems to be prone to overfitting with the terrain data. Test MSEs do not increase for the highest degrees of freedom, even with the OLS-model. The fact that the models was less prone to overfitting in the terrain data case than in the Franke case for given degrees of freedom, is not surprising, The terrain data is more noisy.

Finally for the the terrain case we tested the models on a test set. This test set corresponds to 1/4 of the size of the training set which all analysis was performed on. All test points lay outside the training region. The results on the test set was much weaker than the test MSEs from the cross validations. The Lasso model, which got a negative R2 score, in particular did badly. The reason for this poor fit, is the huge variability in the terrain data. It makes a huge difference whether the testing points is between training points or outside training points!
